<DOC><DOCNO> AP891031-0243 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-89 0845EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-Revco-Bidding     10-31 0204</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Revco-Bidding,0215</SECOND><HEAD>Revco Considers Bid</HEAD><DATELINE>TWINSBURG, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The chairman of Revco D.S. Inc. said thetroubled drug store chain is considering an unsolicited $925million buyout bid from Acadia Partners L.P. and the Robert M. BassGroup.   The proposal would add an estimated $260 million debt to thehighly leveraged company.   Revco, with about 1,900 drugstores in 27 states, is undergoingreorganization under Chapter 11 of the federal Bankruptcy Code.   The company's 1986 billion leveraged buy-out, financed withhigh-interest junk bonds, ran into trouble in 1988. It was thefirst large leveraged-buyout deal of the 1980s to falter.   With the new debt, along with $150 million in cash, thepurchasers would provide $410 million for payments to creditors anddebt interest.   Boake A. Sells, Revco's chairman, said Monday the plan by theFort Worth, Texas, businesses would add to Revco's existing debt of$515 million for a total indebtedness of $775 million.   He said the offer was being studied. He did not say when aresponse would be made.   On Oct. 24, a U.S. bankruptcy judge granted Revco an extensionof its period of exclusivity to file a reorganization plan throughApril, 1990. After that, creditors may file their own plans.</TEXT></DOC>